{"actual_usd":0.125035,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":238,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24293,"reply":"\"I don't think those naturalistic answers hold together very well.\" *I rub a thumb along a faint smear of dried clay on my apron, watching the light shift on the floorboards a moment before I look back at you.* \"Grief-visions might account for one or two people, maybe, but not the whole knot of reports, not the empty tomb sitting there like a stone in the shoe, and not the way frightened men turned stubborn enough to suffer for saying he'd risen.\"\n\n*I ease back a little, the bench giving a soft creak.* \"And the 'didn't really die' road always feels thinner to me still. Roman execution wasn't a casual business. A man half-dead and staggering out of a tomb doesn't found resurrection faith — he'd found pity, horror, maybe a hiding place. The claim Christians insist on is bigger because the thing claimed is bigger: not 'we had powerful experiences after losing him,' but 'death was actually beaten.' If you shave that down to something natural, you've usually explained the fire by explaining away the flame. What part feels strongest to you — the visions idea, or the not-quite-dead one?\"","rolling_24h_usd":83.53071,"run_id":"78bfdc74-fe2c-4733-a248-17f2fdc33394"}
